<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n56126a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56126a">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56126a"> 126(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> e cosi nella / sua grossezza si / rimase e ancor / rimase e ancor / va si sta (p 163 <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n56126a"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Place this by the side of Boccaccio&apos;s favourite formulae: <br>Egli conquisto poi la Scozia, e funne re coronato (ii, 3); <br>Et onorevolmente visse infino alia fine (ii, 4); <br>Molte volte goderono del loro amore: Iddio faccia noi goder del nostro (iii, 6): <br><mark>E cosi nella sua grossezza si rimase e ancor vi si sta</mark> (vi, 8). <p>We have further docked this tail into: &ldquo;And they lived happily ever after.</p> <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE4" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE4"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 163</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Burton is quoting from <cite>The Decameron</cite> of Giovanni Boccaccio (private printing for The Villon Society, London, 1886), translated by his student John Payne (who also, with Burton&apos;s advice) translated the <cite>Thousand Nights and A Night</cite>. In this text, the &apos;tales&apos; each has its own style of concluding. The last words of VI.8 are &ldquo;e cosi nella sua grossezza si rimase e ancor rimase e ancor vi sa sta:&rdquo; = and so she abode in her folly and therein abideth yet. Joyce notes the different endings at 357.29: &ldquo;howdifferend with ...&rdquo;. </mm> </dd></dl>
